{"title_page": "Language interoperability", "text_new": "'''Language interoperability''' is the capability of two different [[programming languages]] to natively interact as part of the same system.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|title=Interoperability in Programming Languages|last=Malone|first=Todd|date=2014|citeseerx = 10.1.1.684.337}}</ref> Interoperability is advantageous, because different programming language are optimized for specific tasks, and allowing them to communicate can create better systems.\n\nThere are many different ways programming languages are interoperable with one another. [[HTML]], [[Cascading Style Sheets|CSS]], and [[JavaScript]] are a form of language interoperability as they work together to render webpages. Some [[object oriented]] languages can do this thanks to the hosting [[virtual machine]] (e.g. [[List of CLI languages|.NET CLI compliant languages]] in the [[Common Language Runtime]] and [[List of JVM languages|JVM compliant languages]] in the [[Java Virtual Machine]]).<ref name=\"ms\">{{cite web|url=https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/subscriptions/50b25433-59f2-4c6f-9774-7d777cde6b0a%28v=vs.90%29|title=Cross-Language Interoperability|year=|publisher=Microsoft Developer Network (msdn.microsoft.com)|accessdate=}}</ref> High-level programming languages are usually interoperable with some lower level languages, an example of this is Apple's [[Swift (programming language)]] and [[Objective-C]].\n\n== Methods for interoperability ==\n\n=== Object models ===\nTo facilitate interoperability between languages, one method is to use [[object model]]s. [[CORBA]] and [[Component Object Model|COM]] are the most popular object models. These standards provide a base set of rules for how object oriented languages would implement their data models to allow for a language-neutral way of implementing objects that can be used in environments different from the one in which they were created.\n\n=== Virtual machines (VMs) ===\n[[File:Common Language Runtime diagram.svg|thumb|Different Languages compile into a shared CLI]]\n[[Virtual machine|A Virtual machine]] is software that emulates operating systems, and acts a buffer between the language and the hardware. This allows a program to run on any hardware or OS. An advantage to VMs can use these type systems to ensure the correctness of participating languages and gives languages a common ground for their type information. Another advantage is that languages designed for VMs compile into a low level intermediate language. The intermediate language then goes through its own compiler or interpreter which can do more types of optimization.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Challenges ==\n\n=== Object model differences ===\nWith object oriented languages attempt to pair containers of data with code, but how each language chooses how to do that may be slightly different. Those design decision do not always map to another language easily. An example of this would be how different languages handle [[Inheritance (object-oriented programming)|inheritance]]. A single class may have zero ([[Go (programming language)|Go]]), one ([[Java (programming language)|Java]]), or many ([[C++]]) [[Superclass (computer science)|superclasses]]. A common approach to this issue is defining a subset of a language that maps directly to the other, but can also fully understand the other language.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chisnall|first=David|date=2013-10-01|title=The Challenge of Cross-language Interoperability|url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=2542661.2543971|journal=Queue|volume=11|issue=10|pages=20|doi=10.1145/2542661.2543971|issn=1542-7730|doi-broken-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> This approach does mean in order for the superset to communicate down it will need to wrap some of its interfaces into classes that can be understood by the subset.\n\n=== Memory models ===\nDifferences in how programming languages handle deallocation of memory is another issue when trying create interoperability. Manual and automatic deallocation is not the only issue but if it has deterministic and nondeterministic destruction. Based on the constraints of the language there are many different strategies for bridging the different behaviors. C++ which uses manual deallocation could use a Java styled garbage collector by changing deallocation behavior to delete the object, but not reclaim the memory. This requires that each object will have to manually be deallocated, in order for the garbage collector to release the memory safely.\n\n=== Mutability ===\nMutability becomes an issue when trying to create interoperability between functional and object oriented languages. Languages like [[Haskell (programming language)|Haskell]] have no mutable types, where in C++ there are some constructs to flag classes as immutable but lack support of determining if something is mutable or not. Many functional types when bridged to object oriented languages can not guarantee that the underlying objects won't be modified.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Foreign function interface]]\n* [[Language-independent specification]]\n* [[Language binding]]\n* [[Glue language]]\n* [[Api#API sharing and reuse via virtual machine|API reuse]]\n* [[List of JVM languages|JVM languages]]\n* [[List of CLI languages|CLI Languages]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Programming languages]]\n", "text_old": "'''Language interoperability''' is the capability of two different [[programming languages]] to natively interact as part of the same system.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|title=Interoperability in Programming Languages|last=Malone|first=Todd|date=2014|citeseerx = 10.1.1.684.337}}</ref> Interoperability is advantageous, because different programming language are optimized for specific tasks, and allowing them to communicate can create better systems.\n\nThere are many different ways programming languages are interoperable with one another. [[HTML]], [[Cascading Style Sheets|CSS]], and [[JavaScript]] are a form of language interoperability as they work together to render webpages. Some [[object oriented]] languages can do this thanks to the hosting [[virtual machine]] (e.g. [[List of CLI languages|.NET CLI compliant languages]] in the [[Common Language Runtime]] and [[List of JVM languages|JVM compliant languages]] in the [[Java Virtual Machine]]).<ref name=\"ms\">{{cite web|url=https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/subscriptions/50b25433-59f2-4c6f-9774-7d777cde6b0a%28v=vs.90%29|title=Cross-Language Interoperability|year=|publisher=Microsoft Developer Network (msdn.microsoft.com)|accessdate=}}</ref> High-level programming languages are usually interoperable with some lower level languages, an example of this is Apple's [[Swift (programming language)]] and [[Objective-C]].\n\n== Methods for interoperability ==\n\n=== Object models ===\nTo facilitate interoperability between languages, one method is to use [[object model]]s. [[CORBA]] and [[Component Object Model|COM]] are the most popular object models. These standards provide a base set of rules for how object oriented languages would implement their data models to allow for a language-neutral way of implementing objects that can be used in environments different from the one in which they were created.\n\n=== Virtual machines (VMs) ===\n[[File:Common Language Runtime diagram.svg|thumb|Different Languages compile into a shared CLI]]\n[[Virtual machine|A Virtual machine]] is software that emulates operating systems, and acts a buffer between the language and the hardware. This allows a program to run on any hardware or OS. An advantage to VMs can use these type systems to ensure the correctness of participating languages and gives languages a common ground for their type information. Another advantage is that languages designed for VMs compile into a low level intermediate language. The intermediate language then goes through its own compiler or interpreter which can do more types of optimization.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Challenges ==\n\n=== Object model differences ===\nWith object oriented languages attempt to pair containers of data with code, but how each language chooses how to do that may be slightly different. Those design decision do not always map to another language easily. An example of this would be how different languages handle [[Inheritance (object-oriented programming)|inheritance]]. On class may have zero ([[Go (programming language)|Go]]), one ([[Java (programming language)|Java]]), or many ([[C++]]) [[Superclass (computer science)|superclasses]]. A common approach to this issue is defining a subset of a language that maps directly to the other, but can also fully understand the other language.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chisnall|first=David|date=2013-10-01|title=The Challenge of Cross-language Interoperability|url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=2542661.2543971|journal=Queue|volume=11|issue=10|pages=20|doi=10.1145/2542661.2543971|issn=1542-7730|doi-broken-date=2019-12-05}}</ref> This approach does mean in order for the superset to communicate down it will need to wrap some of its interfaces into classes that can be understood by the subset.\n\n=== Memory models ===\nDifferences in how programming languages handle deallocation of memory is another issue when trying create interoperability. Manual and automatic deallocation is not the only issue but if it has deterministic and nondeterministic destruction. Based on the constraints of the language there are many different strategies for bridging the different behaviors. C++ which uses manual deallocation could use a Java styled garbage collector by changing deallocation behavior to delete the object, but not reclaim the memory. This requires that each object will have to manually be deallocated, in order for the garbage collector to release the memory safely.\n\n=== Mutability ===\nMutability becomes an issue when trying to create interoperability between functional and object oriented languages. Languages like [[Haskell (programming language)|Haskell]] have no mutable types, where in C++ there are some constructs to flag classes as immutable but lack support of determining if something is mutable or not. Many functional types when bridged to object oriented languages can not guarantee that the underlying objects won't be modified.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Foreign function interface]]\n* [[Language-independent specification]]\n* [[Language binding]]\n* [[Glue language]]\n* [[Api#API sharing and reuse via virtual machine|API reuse]]\n* [[List of JVM languages|JVM languages]]\n* [[List of CLI languages|CLI Languages]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Programming languages]]\n", "name_user": "Divof", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eObject model differences:missed a small typo in the last edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Language_interoperability"}
{"title_page": "Naman Shaw", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name           = Naman Shaw\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1986|12|18}}\n| birth_place    = [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]], [[India]]\n| birth_name     = Naman Shaw\n| occupation     = [[Actor]]\n| yearsactive    = 2004 \u2013 present\n| spouse         = \n}}\n\n'''Naman Shaw''' (born December 18, 1986)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pinkvilla.com/tv/scoops/346639/naman-shaw-plans-celebrate-birthday-his-whatsapp-group | title=Naman Shaw plans to celebrate birthday with his Whatsapp group! | work=PinkVilla | date=18 December 2015 | accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> is an [[India]]n [[television actor]] notable for his roles as Pushkar Shukla in [[Zee TV]]'s drama series ''[[Kasamh Se]]'', as Nakul Virani in [[STAR Plus]]'s series ''[[Kyunki Saas Bhi Kabhi Bahu Thi]]'' and in ''[[Kasautii Zindagii Kay (2001 TV series)|Kasautii Zindagii Kay]]'' as Nihaal Garewal. Naman Shaw has also played small roles in other serials such as a brief role in ''[[Kasturi (TV series)|Kasturi]]'' as Kasturi's fiance, Girish. Later he had a brief role in [[Kahe Naa Kahe]] as Vidhyud on [[9X (TV channel)|9X]] channel. Naman Shaw married Neha Mishra on 23 November 2017.\n\nShaw began his acting career through participating in [[Zee TV]]'s talent hunt show, ''[[India's Best Cinestars Ki Khoj]]'' in 2004 where he made the Top 15. He also appeared in [[Nach Baliye 4]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Nach-Baliye-Naman-Shaw-supports-Himmanshoo-Malhotra/articleshow/48113197.cms | title=Nach Baliye: Naman Shaw supports Himmanshoo Malhotra | work=The Times of India | date=17 July 2015 | accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> He was seen in [[Colors TV]]'s popular show ''[[Kairee \u2014 Rishta Khatta Meetha]]''<ref>{{cite web | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Naman-Shaw-eats-snake-in-China/articleshow/39948772.cms | title=Naman Shaw eats snake in China | work=The Times of India | date=10 August 2014 | accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> as Anuj replacing [[Jay Bhanushali]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/TV-celebs-embroiled-in-controversies/photostory/49540168.cms | title=TV celebs embroiled in controversies | work=The Times of India | accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|- style=\"bacground:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! scop=\"col\"| Year \n! scop=\"col\"| Work \n! scop=\"col\"| Role \n! scop=\"col\"| Channel\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[India's Best Cinestars Ki Khoj]]'' || Himself ||[[Zee TV]]\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Kasamh Se]]'' || Pushkar Shukla|| [[Zee TV]]\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Kyunki Saas Bhi Kabhi Bahu Thi]]'' || Nakul Virani || [[STAR Plus]]\n|-\n| 2007-2008 || ''[[Kasautii Zindagii Kay (2001 TV series)|Kasautii Zindagii Kay]]'' || Nihal Garewal || [[STAR Plus]]\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Kasturi (TV series)|Kasturi]]'' || Girish || [[STAR Plus]]\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Kahe Naa Kahe]]'' || Vidhyud || [[9X (TV channel)|9X]]\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Kaun Jeetega Bollywood Ka Ticket]]'' || Contestant || [[9X (TV channel)|9X]]\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Nach Baliye 4]]'' || Himself || [[Star Plus]]\n|-\n| ||''[[Sssshhh... Phir Koi Hai|Amrauli Ke Darinde]]''|| Arjun || [[STAR One]]\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Jeet Jayenge Hum]]'' || Prabhakar || [[Sony Entertainment Television (India)|Sony TV]]\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Ssshhhh...Phir Koi Hai|Trittya]] || Ajinkya || [[STAR One]]\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Rakt Sambandh]]'' || Niraj || [[Imagine TV]]\n|-\n| 2011-2012 || ''[[Beend Banoongaa Ghodi Chadhunga]]'' || Jai Poddar || [[Imagine TV]]\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Kairee \u2014 Rishta Khatta Meetha]]'' || Anuj Shrivastav/Abhay Shrivastav || [[Colors (TV channel)|Colors]]\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Khushiyon Kii Gullak Aashi]]'' || Vishesh Doobey || [[Sony Pal]]\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Piya Rang